⏺ Movie Ticket Booking — Complete Python Implementation

  ---
  Step 1: Core Value Objects (Frozen Dataclasses)

  from dataclasses import dataclass, field
  from enum import Enum
  from typing import Dict, List, Optional, Set
  from datetime import datetime, timedelta
  import threading
  import uuid
  import time

  Why frozen dataclasses? These are immutable facts — a Movie's title never changes mid-session. frozen=True gives you free __hash__ so you can put them in sets/dicts, and prevents accidental mutation.

  @dataclass(frozen=True)
  class Movie:
      id: str
      title: str
      duration_minutes: int
      genre: str

  @dataclass(frozen=True)
  class Seat:
      row: str        # "A", "B", "C"
      number: int     # 1, 2, 3 ...
      seat_type: str  # "STANDARD", "PREMIUM", "HANDICAP"

      def label(self) -> str:
          return f"{self.row}{self.number}"   # "A1", "B12"

  Why seat_type on Seat (not Showtime)? The physical seat doesn't change — A1 is always premium if the theater built it that way. Pricing can differ per showtime, but the seat type is structural.

  ---
  Step 2: SeatStatus Enum + Hold Logic

  class SeatStatus(Enum):
      AVAILABLE = "available"
      HELD = "held"           # temporary lock (10 min timer)
      BOOKED = "booked"       # payment confirmed
      BLOCKED = "blocked"     # maintenance / broken seat

  Why HELD separate from BOOKED?
  - User clicks "Select Seat A1" → status = HELD (15 min to pay)
  - User pays → status = BOOKED
  - User abandons → timer expires → status = AVAILABLE again
  - Without HELD, two users could both "book" A1 simultaneously

  @dataclass
  class SeatHold:
      seat: Seat
      user_id: str
      held_until: datetime    # hold expires at this time
      hold_id: str = field(default_factory=lambda: str(uuid.uuid4()))

